Analysis of BSE Intraday Returns

Meghana Yerabati

22 August, 2017

Problem Statement

We aim to find the distribution of intraday returns of institutional traders and retail traders by studying the the bse tradebook to deduce the patterns of wealth transfer amongst institutional and retail intraday traders.

This is an R Markdown document. Markdown is a simple formatting syntax for authoring HTML, PDF, and MS Word documents.

Results

A short analysis for data of five days is given below.

The dataset consists of 8 columns:

Schema Description
date Date on which the trade occured
trader BSE client code
symbol BSE Scrip Code for the stock
cat BSE client category
buy_vol total volume of a given stock bought by the client on the given date
sell_vol total volume of a given stock sold by the client on the given date
vwap_sell calculation explained below
vwap_buy calculation explained below

The methodology for calculation of Volume Weighted Average Price (VWAP) of a given stock for a given trader is as follows:

\[VWAP_{buy}= \dfrac{\Sigma\,vol_{buy}*P_{buy}}{\Sigma \,vol_{buy} }\]

\[VWAP_{sell}= \dfrac{\Sigma\,vol_{sell}*P_{sell}}{\Sigma \,vol_{sell} }\]

Analysing the institutional and retail traders returns

Normalize returns earned by the traders:

We normalize the returns earned by the traders with respect to volume in the following way:

\[ Normalized \, Returns= \dfrac{Total\,volume\,weighted \,logarithmic\,returns\,earned\,by\, the\,trader}{Total\, volume\, traded\, by\, the\, trader} \]

\[Normalized \, Returns=\dfrac{\Sigma log(VWAP_{sell}/VWAP_{buy})*min(vol_{buy},vol_{sell}))}{\Sigma\,min(vol_{buy},vol_{sell}) }\]

We run the analysis only for category types Individual or I and Company or CO where the former are retail traders and the latter are institutional traders.

Q-Q Plot:

  1. A kernel density estimate is used to display the distribution of variables with underlying smoothness using geom_density in ggplot2 with the default kernel being gaussian. The bandwidth of a Gaussian kernel density estimator defaults to 0.9 times the minimum of the standard deviation and the interquartile range divided by 1.34 times the sample size to the negative one-fifth power (= Silvermans rule of thumb, Silverman (1986, page 48, eqn (3.31)) unless the quartiles coincide when a positive result will be guaranteed. Bandwidh adjusting factor is 0.5
